  "prompt": "Isn't money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** is **illegal** in virtually every country around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (from activities like drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, or other crimes) appear legitimate by funneling it through legitimate businesses or financial systems.\n\nHere\u2019s a breakdown of why it\u2019s illegal and how it\u2019s typically addressed:\n\n1. **Criminalization**: Money laundering is explicitly outlawed under national laws and international agreements. For example, the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** sets global standards to combat money laundering.\n\n2. **Harm to Society**: Money laundering enables and perpetuates criminal activities by allowing criminals to profit from their illegal actions. This undermines the economy, fuels corruption, and often finances terrorism.\n\n3. **Three Stages of Money Laundering**:\n   - **Placement**: Introducing illicit funds into the financial system.\n   - **Layering**: Concealing the origin of the funds through complex transactions.\n   - **Integration**: Reintroducing the \u201ccleaned\u201d money into the economy as legitimate funds.\n\n4. **Consequences**: Individuals or organizations involved in money laundering face severe penalties, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.\n\nGovernments and financial institutions work together to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering through regulations like **Anti-Money Laundering (AML)** laws and **Know Your Customer (KYC)** requirements.",
